{"result": {"response": {"id": "chatcmpl-E52FynZiTCc4X1EP7Y5n6FdK7Fg4c", "choices": [{"finish_reason": "stop", "index": 0, "logprobs": null, "message": {"content": "{\n  \"title\": \"NCCN Prostate Cancer CRPC Protocols (PROS-16, PROS-17)\",\n  \"summary\": \"This community centers on the NCCN Prostate Cancer treatment protocols, particularly focusing on the management of M0 and M1 Castration-Resistant Prostate Cancer (CRPC). The main entities are the protocol pages (PROS-16 for M0 CRPC and PROS-17 for M1 CRPC), specific clinical states (no metastases, metastases, adenocarcinoma, small cell/neuroendocrine), and a structured set of procedural and therapeutic options. The protocols interlink clinical findings, monitoring, imaging, histological phenotyping, and recommendations for sequential therapy, together forming a comprehensive and evidence-based pathway for patients with advanced prostate cancer. The high degree of interconnection and the critical nature of these recommendations underpin the significant clinical impact of this community.\",\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"PROS-16 is the central guideline for M0 CRPC workup and treatment.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"The PROS-16 protocol serves as the main guideline for the diagnosis and management of M0 Castration-Resistant Prostate Cancer (CRPC) patients with no detectable metastases. It integrates a cascade of steps including imaging studies to rule out distant metastases, continued androgen deprivation therapy (ADT), periodic disease assessments (both PSA and imaging-based), and determination of whether current treatment should be maintained or escalated. The protocol provides structured guidance for escalating care upon evidence of disease progression, making it instrumental in patient management [Data: Entities (49, 50, 60, 55, 62, 51, 53, 54), Relationships (151, 161, 164, 165, 166, 167, 169, 170, 172, 174, 178, +more)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Routine imaging and PSA monitoring facilitate early detection of disease progression.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"One of the protocol's cornerstone recommendations is regular periodic imaging and serum PSA (prostate-specific antigen) assessments for patients in the M0 CRPC state. Imaging studies are specifically used to detect conversion from M0 (no metastases) to M1 (metastatic disease), triggering adjustments to the treatment regimen. In cases where PSA is stable and there is no evidence of metastasis, the protocol supports maintaining the current therapy with continued surveillance. This approach reflects optimal resource use and reduces unnecessary overtreatment [Data: Entities (50, 60, 58, 55, 62, 59), Relationships (161, 164, 175, 178)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Escalation of therapy is guided by PSA doubling time and radiographic findings.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"The guideline incorporates PSA Doubling Time (PSADT) as a critical metric; a rapidly rising PSA, even in the absence of radiographic metastases, can justify intensifying therapy. The transition toward more advanced therapies is also prompted by imaging evidence of metastases. The protocol facilitates risk stratification and timely adjustments, which are pivotal for improving patient outcomes and delaying overt progression [Data: Entities (52, 57, 59), Relationships (166, 167, 172, 174)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Preferred and secondary agents—apalutamide, darolutamide, enzalutamide—are recommended for M0 CRPC.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"For M0 CRPC, the guideline recommends using category 1 agents such as apalutamide, darolutamide, and enzalutamide. These are androgen receptor pathway inhibitors with proven benefits in prolonging metastasis-free survival. Other secondary hormone therapies may be considered for patients who cannot tolerate or access these agents. The protocol categorizes these options and recommends them based on efficacy, tolerance, and patient factors [Data: Entities (54, 53), Relationships (170, 169)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"The transition to M1 CRPC is addressed by PROS-17 with systemic therapy recommendations.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"For patients who develop metastases—designated as M1 CRPC—the management transitions to the PROS-17 guideline, which emphasizes systemic therapies including chemotherapy (like cisplatin, etoposide, docetaxel, cabazitaxel), and directs clinicians to reference small cell lung cancer protocols for neuroendocrine subtypes. The explicit structure facilitates tailored therapy selection based on histologic and molecular features [Data: Entities (69, 70, 61, 68), Relationships (186, 187, 177, 194)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Ongoing ADT is universal in CRPC protocols.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Across both the M0 and M1 CRPC protocols, the recommendation to continue ADT (to maintain castrate serum testosterone <50 ng/dL) is universal and foundational. This is reinforced at multiple decision nodes, regardless of clinical stage or subsequent therapy, reflecting its critical role in disease management [Data: Entities (51, 65), Relationships (165, 189, 190)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Molecular and pathological subtyping guide further personalized management.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"The community places strong emphasis on workup for histological classification (adenocarcinoma versus small cell/neuroendocrine subtypes) and somatic/molecular testing, such as for HRR (homologous recombination repair), MSI/dMMR, and TMB. These results steer treatment toward highly personalized regimens and may include targeted therapies or enrollment in clinical trials, enhancing the precision of care [Data: Entities (64, 66, 67, 68), Relationships (190, 191, 194, 189)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Supportive care and management of bone metastases are integrated into systemic therapy plans.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"For M1 CRPC patients, especially those with bone metastases, the protocol recommends bone-targeting agents (denosumab or zoledronic acid), palliative radiotherapy for painful lesions, and structured supportive care. These adjunct strategies are critical for reducing morbidity and maintaining quality of life during systemic therapies [Data: Entities (65), Relationships (189)].\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"rating\": 9.0,\n  \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high because these guidelines directly inform the standard of care and significantly affect clinical outcomes for a large population of prostate cancer patients.\"\n}", "refusal": null, "role": "assistant", "annotations": [], "audio": null, "function_call": null, "tool_calls": null, "provider_specific_fields": {"refusal": null}}, "provider_specific_fields": {}}], "created": 1784869022, "model": "gpt-4.1-2025-04-14", "object": "chat.completion", "moderation": null, "service_tier": "default", "system_fingerprint": "fp_59cee91353", "usage": {"completion_tokens": 1380, "prompt_tokens": 3440, "total_tokens": 4820, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": 0, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 0, "rejected_prediction_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cache_write_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 0}}, "formatted_response": null, "content": "{\n  \"title\": \"NCCN Prostate Cancer CRPC Protocols (PROS-16, PROS-17)\",\n  \"summary\": \"This community centers on the NCCN Prostate Cancer treatment protocols, particularly focusing on the management of M0 and M1 Castration-Resistant Prostate Cancer (CRPC). The main entities are the protocol pages (PROS-16 for M0 CRPC and PROS-17 for M1 CRPC), specific clinical states (no metastases, metastases, adenocarcinoma, small cell/neuroendocrine), and a structured set of procedural and therapeutic options. The protocols interlink clinical findings, monitoring, imaging, histological phenotyping, and recommendations for sequential therapy, together forming a comprehensive and evidence-based